Why America's President Bush cannot be re-elected again
I have never been particularly engaged in party politics, but these are not normal times.
President George W. Bush endangers the security of the United States and the world and at the same time undermines American values.
Due to my opposition to him, I have been damned by Bush's campaign team.
President Bush ran in the year 2000 with a campaign program that promised a foreign policy of "humility".
If he is re-elected, this will be a vote for the Bush doctrine of preemptive war - and the invasion of Iraq - and the world will have to live with the consequences.
By rejecting Bush's policy at the ballot boxes, America has a chance to regain respect and support from the world.
The 9/11 terrorist attacks required a strong response.
However, they have also led to the abolition of the indispensable critical process for democracy - the comprehensive and honest discussion of the impending problems.
Bush silenced criticism by declaring it unpatriotic.
For a duration of 18 months following 9/11, he managed to suppress any dissent.
In this way, he has led America in the wrong direction.
In fact, Bush has directly played Osama bin Laden into the hands of others.
The invasion of Afghanistan - where bin Laden lived and Al Qaida maintained its training camps - was justified.
The invasion of Iraq was not.
He was an unintended gift of Bush to bin Laden.
Immediately after September 11, spontaneous expressions of sympathy towards America were seen all over the world.
These have been replaced by widespread disillusionment.
More people than on September 11 are today willing to risk their lives to kill Americans.
Bush likes to claim that the terrorists hate Americans for what they are - a freedom-loving people - and not for what they do.
War and occupation however produce innocent victims.
We Americans count our fallen soldiers - more than 1,000 in Iraq.
The rest of the world also counts the Iraqis killed every day - perhaps twenty times as many.
Not least, torture of inmates in Abu Ghraib prison was not the work of a few "bad apples" either.
It was part of a system for dealing with prisoners set up by Defense Minister Donald Rumsfeld.
The world public condemns America, and our troops in Iraq are paying the price for it.
Bush has convinced people that America's security is in good hands with him, by addressing the fears triggered by the September 11 attacks.
In times of danger, people rally around their flag, and Bush has exploited this by promoting a sense of vulnerability.
His election campaign assumes that people are ultimately not interested in the truth and will almost believe anything if it's repeated often enough.
Something must be wrong with America if we fall for it.
For example, about 40% of Americans still believe that Saddam Hussein had something to do with 9/11, although the 9/11 Commission - set up by Bush and chaired by a Republican - has clearly established that no such connection existed.
One wants to scream: "Wake up, America."
Don't you realize we're being led around by the nose?"
The war in Iraq was based on false assumptions from start to finish - if it were to end.
It was a war of choice, not necessity.
Moreover, America has been drawn into war under a pretext: mass destruction weapons could not be found, and a connection to Al Qaida cannot be proven.
Bush then claimed that America was drawn into war to free Iraq.
But democracy cannot be imposed on anyone by force.
Saddam Hussein was a tyrant, and the Iraqis - and the world - can be glad to be rid of him.
America, however, had the duty to ensure law and order; instead, we saw the plundering of Baghdad and other cities without intervening.
If it was really about the Iraqi people, we would have had to provide a larger number of soldiers for the occupation.
We would not only have had to protect the Oil Ministry, but also other ministries, museums and hospitals.
Even worse: Where American soldiers encountered resistance, they used methods - such as breaking into private homes and mistreating prisoners - that shocked and humiliated the population and triggered resentment and anger.
The Bush administration's retreats and blunders are legion.
First, the Iraqi army was dissolved, then the US tried to rebuild it.
First, the US tried to remove the Baathists, then America sought their help.
When the uprisings could no longer be managed, America installed an Iraqi government.
The man destined to be their leader was a CIAs protégé with a reputation as a "strong man" - an undemocratic decision by all means.
Despite the efforts of Bush's election campaign team to sugarcoat the situation, the situation in Iraq is bleak.
A large part of the western region was left to the insurgents. The prospects of holding free and fair elections in January are rapidly receding.
Civil War Looms.
Bush's War in Iraq Has Caused Unfathomable Damage to America, Weakened Its Military Strength, and Undermined the Morale of the Troops.
Before the War, America Could Project an Impression of Overwhelming Strength.
No Longer.
Afghanistan Is Slipping Out of Control.
Nordkorea, the Iran, Pakistan and further countries pursue nuclear programs with renewed energy.
One can criticize the Bush administration in many other political questions, but none is as significant as Iraq.
The costs of the war amount to nearly 200 billion dollars so far and will continue to rise, since the invasion of Iraq was much easier than the withdrawal will be.
Bush has made a personal attack on John Kerry, asking him to explain what he would do differently.
Kerry responded that he would have done everything differently and that he would be in a better situation to free us from our entanglement.
Aber auch ihm wird dies nicht leicht fallen, denn Amerika steckt in einem Sumpf.
Führende Militärexperten und Diplomaten haben Bush händeringend gewarnt, nicht in den Irak einzumarschieren.
Er hat sie ignoriert.
Er hat den kritischen Prozess unterdrückt, mit dem Argument, dass jede Kritik am Oberbefehlshaber die US-Truppen gefährde.
Aber dies ist Bushs Krieg, und er sollte dafür zur Verantwortung gezogen werden.
Americans should take a moment to pause and ask themselves: Whom do we owe this mess to?
A moment's reflection may raise another question: Does Bush's cowboy demeanor qualify him to remain America's commander-in-chief?
